<section id="the-problem-with-cpi-u-for-insurance" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="the-problem-with-cpi-u-for-insurance">The Problem with CPI-U for Insurance</h2>
<p>The standard Consumer Price Index (CPI-U) is designed to measure inflation for typical household consumption. But for Property &amp; Casualty insurance actuaries, it significantly underweights the cost components that actually drive claims severity:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Medical care</strong> gets only ~6% weight in CPI-U, while bodily injury claims can be 30-50% of auto liability losses</li>
<li><strong>Shelter</strong> receives ~33% but doesn’t reflect specific materials and labor costs in property claims</li>
<li><strong>Auto repair</strong>, hospital costs, and physician fees are underrepresented relative to claims exposure</li>
</ul>
<p>This creates a systematic gap when using CPI-U for loss trending and rate adequacy analysis.</p>
</section>
<section id="a-custom-solution" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="a-custom-solution">A Custom Solution</h2>
<p>I built a <strong>P&amp;C Severity CPI</strong> that reweights Bureau of Labor Statistics CPI components to better approximate the inflation experienced in insurance claims payments.</p>
<section id="index-weights" class="level3">
<h3 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="index-weights">Index Weights</h3>
<table class="caption-top table">
<colgroup>
<col style="width: 30%">
<col style="width: 24%">
<col style="width: 45%">
</colgroup>
<thead>
<tr class="header">
<th>Category</th>
<th>Weight</th>
<th>P&amp;C Rationale</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr class="odd">
<td>Auto Repair</td>
<td>20%</td>
<td>Parts, labor, glass, paint for auto PD and collision</td>
</tr>
<tr class="even">
<td>Physicians</td>
<td>15%</td>
<td>Medical evaluations, IMEs, treatment costs in BI claims</td>
</tr>
<tr class="odd">
<td>Hospital</td>
<td>15%</td>
<td>Inpatient costs for severe bodily injury claims</td>
</tr>
<tr class="even">
<td>Shelter</td>
<td>20%</td>
<td>Proxy for construction/rebuild costs (lumber, labor)</td>
</tr>
<tr class="odd">
<td>Core CPI (Wages)</td>
<td>15%</td>
<td>Legal fees, adjusters, administrative costs</td>
</tr>
<tr class="even">
<td>Core CPI (General)</td>
<td>15%</td>
<td>Residual services, general inflation exposure</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</section>
<section id="the-formula" class="level3">
<h3 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="the-formula">The Formula</h3>
<p>The index is calculated as:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Ctext%7BP%5C&amp;C%5C_CPI%7D(t)%20=%20%5Csum_i%20w_i%20%5Ctimes%20%5Cfrac%7B%5Ctext%7BCPI%7D_i(t)%7D%7B%5Ctext%7BCPI%7D_i(2010)%7D%20%5Ctimes%20100"></p>
<p>Where:</p>
<ul>
<li><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?w_i"> = weight assigned to component <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?i"> (summing to 1.0)</li>
<li><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Ctext%7BCPI%7D_i(t)"> = BLS CPI index value for component <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?i"> at time <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?t"></li>
<li>January 2010 is the base period (= 100)</li>
</ul>
</section>
</section>
